  "prompt": "Where can I find comedic monologues from published plays?",
  "response": "You can find comedic monologues from published plays in several places:\n\n1. **Play Anthologies**: Many collections of plays contain monologues. Look for anthologies that focus on comedic plays or those that feature contemporary works.\n\n2. **Online Libraries**: Websites such as Project Gutenberg and Internet Archive offer various texts, including plays that can be freely accessed.\n\n3. **Theater Websites**: Websites like Dramatists Play Service, Samuel French, and Playscripts often have selected monologues from their published plays. They may require you to purchase scripts, but some may provide excerpts for free.\n\n4. **Acting Resources**: Books specifically focused on monologues for actors often include comedic pieces. Examples include \"The Ultimate Audition Book\" series or \"Monologues for Young Actors.\"\n\n5. **Educational Institutions**: Many drama schools and universities provide online resources or libraries that list comedic monologues for students.\n\n6. **Online Forums and Communities**: Websites like Reddit, StageMilk, and TheaterMania often have threads where users share and discuss monologue recommendations.\n\n7. **YouTube**: You can find performances of monologues from plays that may include comedic pieces, which might give you a good sense of tone and delivery.\n\nIf you're looking for something specific, I can help suggest particular plays or monologues!",
